				<section id="PostHarvestHandling">
					<div class="">
						<h4>Post-Harvest Handling</h4>
						<p>Post- harvest handling is key in determining the quality of household meals and hence nutrition. The way crops are handled after harvesting determines safety of food in terms of contamination. Post-harvest handling is a critical entry point for germs. </p>
						<p>Traditionally in our Ugandan culture, communities have a belief that once harvested; crops have to be dried on bare ground in order to boost the taste of the meals. This is a risky practice because such crops are exposed to contamination and hence affecting quality of food. On consumption, since these crops are already contaminated, they lead to diarrhea which does not allow the bodies absorb the nutrients hence causing malnutrition in the vulnerable groups.</p>
						<p>As Goshen’s Fountain of Nutrition and Health, we have interventions of sensitizing household farmers on the benefits of good post-harvest handling that range from food safety to good market prices for their produce. </p>
						<p>Farmers are trained on how to make raised platforms of stones and timber on which bags of produce are placed to avoid spoilage. Farmers also trained on how to use local affordable preservation methods like application of ash. Farmers are encouraged to dry their produce on tarpaulins though most of them face a challenge of affordability.</p>
					</div>
				</section>
				<section id="SchoolHealthProgram">
					<div class="">
						<h4>School Health Program</h4>
						<p>Goshen’s Fountain of Nutrition and Health has a program of promoting nutrition and health in schools. This is program is aimed at Integrating Food and Nutrition, Health, Agricultural and Environmental Education in schools for sustainable development.</p>
						<p>As Goshen’s Fountain of Nutrition and Health we conduct awareness in schools on the benefits of adopting a school health program.</p>
						<p>Among others, we also support schools start out small vegetable gardens and encourage them to feed students on green leafy vegetables for balance dieting.</p>
					</div>
