				<section id="WaterSanitationHygiene">
					<div class="">
						<h4>Water, Sanitation and Hygiene</h4>
						<p>Diarrhea caused by poor sanitation, lack of hygiene and unsafe water is one of the leading causes of child health death globally, and the leading cause of death in sub- Sahara Africa. Worse yet, diarrheal diseases inhabit nutrient absorption leading to starvation even if sufficient nutrition is consumed. Under nutrition also reduces a child’s resistance to subsequent infections. Even if diarrhea does not kill outright, repeated bouts during early childhood negatively impact physical and cognitive development.</p>
						<p>There is emerging evidence that the intestinal disease known as environmental enteropathy also has an effect on child growth. Environmental enteropathy affects the small intestines and is the result of chronic child exposure to fecal microbes due to poor sanitation. It also reduces the child’s ability to absorb nutrients.</p>
						<p>Safe drinking water, proper sanitation and hygiene can prevent under nutrition and stunting in children by preventing development of environmental enteropathy and diarrheal diseases.</p>
						<p>Children living in households with proper sanitation and hygiene are taller for their age, or less stunted, compared to children living in contaminated environments.</p>
						<p>As Goshen’s Fountain of Nutrition and Health, we promote hand washing with soap as an element of hygiene programming and this can reduce the incidence of diarrhea. Hand washing, water quality treatment, sanitation and hygiene are core interventions for maternal and child under nutrition and survival.</p>
						<p>As Goshen’s Fountain of Nutrition and Health, we carry out activities aimed at encouraging households to each have a latrine to avoid open defecation. Toilets have a significant effect on children’s health and nutrition. Access to toilets can help children reach their full physical and mental potential. Likewise, the absence of toilets can have profound implications on the children. Imagine in an environment without latrines means people practice open defecation in the same fields where children play whereby they put their fingers in their mouths without knowing the contaminants on their fingers.</p>
						<p>To promote this objective, we do community sensitization where households are reminded of the dangers of open defecation and are encouraged to construct latrines. We also sensitize communities on the importance of hand washing after visiting the latrines and the likely dangers in terms of disease exposure. We distribute 5 liter empty jerry cans to households where they keep water for washing hands after a latrine visit.</p>
						<p>We also do household visits as a form of onsite inspection together with the local leaders to engage families without latrines to ensure they construct them.</p>
						<p>In a bid to promote safe water, we encourage communities to have protected well springs to avoid contamination.</p>
					</div>
				</section>
				<section id="SupportOfOVC">
					<div class="">
						<h4>Support of the Orphans and Vulnerable Children (OVC) and other vulnerable groups</h4>
						<p>Goshen’s Fountains of Nutrition and Health offers support of the OVCs and other vulnerable groups like pregnant and lactating mothers, the elderly and PLWHIV. We offer support to OVCs that are infected and affected by the HIV epidemic.</p>
						<p>We have enrolled 300 OVCs for support under our programs. They need support for scholastic requirements, nutrition support, and skills empowerment for the grownups.</p>
						<p>To the affected groups, we do pre testing counseling; we do HIV screening and post testing counseling for both those found to be positive and negative. The positive are linked to care.</p>
						<p>For OVCs who have already known their status to be HIV positive, we link them to care and we emphasize to them the importance of compliance with the ARV taking. We offer them posttest counseling also highlighting nutrition.</p>
						<p>For OVCs who are found negative, we sensitize on prevention and they undergo counseling sessions on the dangers of HIV, how it is transmitted and how to keep themselves free from being infected.</p>
						<p>We also support in their education needs like scholastic materials for those ready to continue with education. We also lobby for bursaries from other stake holders.</p>
						<p>We offer vocational training to OVCs that are ready for skills. Some of the programs offered are; craft making, metal fabrication, liquid soap making, tailoring, charcoal lighter making, Jewelry making.</p>
					</div>
				</section>
				<section id="EconomicEmpowerment">
					<div class="">
						<h4>Economic Empowerment for the Youth, OVCs and Low Income Women</h4>
						<p>As Goshen’s Fountain of Nutrition and Health, we run a program aimed at empowering the vulnerable groups with hands-on skill that will enable them make a living. The incomes enable the households take care of their nutrition and other household needs. We train them in craft making; we offer financial literacy training, tailoring and knitting, baking.</p>
						<p>Goshen’s Fountain of Nutrition and Health believes in economic empowerment for sustainability rather than giving food and cash handouts.  Once empowered, households are able to take care of their total needs and can also support others.</p>
						<p>Household Economic Strengthening is the ideal solution to eradicating poverty, malnutrition and disease which are the biggest global challenges leading to death.</p>
					</div>
